<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06147088 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06147088 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  AIDS; MEDICAL; DRUG; LAWSUIT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc. will pay $600,000 to settle a federal lawsuitaccusing the firm of distributing an unauthorized AIDS treatment.;    Thepharmaceutical firm agreed Friday to the settlement without admittingwrongdoing. ICN, headquartered in Costa Mesa, distributed the anti-viral drugVirazole as an AIDS treatment without government approval.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AIDS TREATMENT LAWSUIT SETTLED  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The company will pay a $400,000 fine and reimburse the federal Food andDrug Administration $200,000 for administrative costs.;    The action filed bythe U.S. Justice Department alleged ICN gave six doctors Virazole, also knownas Ribavirin, to prevent or delay the progression of AIDS.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Costa Mesa  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910526  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  94  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday May 26, 199100147088,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>